{{TOC right}} ==The Group of Order 2== Here is the group table for the only group of order 2
{| |+ Z<sub>2</sub> |- style="background:gray;color:white" !+ || 0 || 1 |- ! style="background:gray;color:white" | 0 || 0 || 1 |- ! style="background:gray;color:white" | 1 || 1 || 0 |}
==The Group of Order 3== Here is the group table for the only group of order 3
{| |+ Z<sub>3</sub> |- style="background:gray;color:white" !+ || 0 || 1 || 2 |- ! style="background:gray;color:white" | 0 || 0 || 1 || 2 |- ! style="background:gray;color:white" | 1 || 1 || 2 || 0 |- ! style="background:gray;color:white" | 2 || 2 || 0 || 1 |}
==The Groups of Order 4== Here are the group tables for the only groups of order 4 ===The cyclic group of order 4=== {| border=0 | align="center" colspan= 7 | Two ways of documenting the same group structure |- | align="center" colspan=3 | {| border=0 |+ colspan=5 | Z<sub>4</sub> |- style="background:gray;color:white" !+ || 0 || 1 || 2 || 3 |- ! style="background:gray;color:white" | 0 || 0 || 1 || 2 || 3 |- ! style="background:gray;color:white" | 1 || 1 || 2 || 3 || 0 |- ! style="background:gray;color:white" | 2 || 2 || 3 || 0 || 1 |- ! style="background:gray;color:white" | 3 || 3 || 0 || 1 || 2 |} || | align="center" colspan=3| {| |+ <math>Z^*_5</math> |- style="background:gray;color:#ffdead" !&times; || 1 || 2 || 3 || 4 |- ! style="background:gray; color:#ffdead" | 1 || 1 || 2 || 3 || 4 |- ! style="background:gray; color:#ffdead" | 2 || 2 || 4 || 1 || 3 |- ! style="background:gray; color:#ffdead" | 3 || 3 || 1 || 4 || 2 |- ! style="background:gray; color:#ffdead" | 4 || 4 || 3 || 2 || 1 |} |- | colspan=7 | To see more clearly that these two tables actually have the same |- | colspan=7 | group structure you'll need to rename the entries |- | &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; | style="background:gray;color:white;" align=center |0|| &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; || maps to || &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; || style="background:gray; color:#ffdead" align=center |1 ||&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; |- | | style="background:gray;color:white;" align=center |1|| || maps to || || style="background:gray; color:#ffdead" align=center |2 || |- | | style="background:gray;color:white;" align=center |2|| || maps to || || style="background:gray; color:#ffdead" align=center |4 || |- | | style="background:gray;color:white;" align=center |3|| || maps to || || style="background:gray; color:#ffdead" align=center |3 || |- | colspan=3 style="background:gray;color:white;" align=center |1 + 2 = 3 | maps to | colspan=3 style="background:gray; color:#ffdead" align=center |2 &times; 4 = 3 |} Notice that regardless of the way we notate this group, there is an element that generates the whole group. <math>1 + 1 \to 2 \quad 1 + 2 \to 3 \quad 1 + 3 \to 0</math> <math> 2{}\times{} 2 \to 4 \quad 2 \times 4 \to 3 \quad 2 \times 3 \to 1 </math>
===The other group of order 4=== For the following example, image the number 0 through 3 written in binary, then add the digits without any carrying. For example, 2 + 3 10 + 11 01 1 Since binary addition (without carry) is isomorphic to <math>Z_2</math> we view this group as being two copies of <math>Z_2</math> joined together. That's where the name comes from. {| |+ <math>Z_2 \oplus Z_2 </math> |- style="background:gray;color:white" !+ || 0 || 1 || 2 || 3 |- ! style="background:gray;color:white" | 0 || 0 || 1 || 2 || 3 |- ! style="background:gray;color:white" | 1 || 1 || 0 || 3 || 2 |- ! style="background:gray;color:white" | 2 || 2 || 3 || 0 || 1 |- ! style="background:gray;color:white" | 3 || 3 || 2 || 1 || 0 |}
==The Group of Order 5== {| |+ <math>Z_5 </math> |- style="background:gray;color:white" !+ || 0 || 1 || 2 || 3 || 4 |- ! style="background:gray;color:white" | 0 || 0 || 1 || 2 || 3 || 4 |- ! style="background:gray;color:white" | 1 || 1 || 2 || 3 || 4 || 0 |- ! style="background:gray;color:white" | 2 || 2 || 3 || 4 || 0 || 1 |- ! style="background:gray;color:white" | 3 || 3 || 4 || 0 || 1 || 2 |- ! style="background:gray;color:white" | 4 || 4 || 0 || 1 || 2 || 3 |}
